  <div class="row section action--stage action--stage-inactive">
    <h3>Step 3: Do</h3>
    <p class="summary">How to compost your food&hellip;</p>
    <div class="action--description">
      <p>On a regular basis, empty out your collection bins into the compost pile. Make sure you mix a combination of green and brown waste. Green waste includes fruit and vegetable scraps, grass clippings, and tea bags. Brown waste includes things like bread, food-soiled cardboard, dead plants, and leaves.</p>
      <p>Make sure you mix your compost pile every week or two. Your custodians shovels or pitchforks would work great for this. This will ensure there is enough air in the pile for the material to properly decompose.</p>
      <p>When you mix your pile, take a hose and add some water as well. You want your pile to be as wet as a wrung out sponge.</p>
      <p>You should also take this time to monitor the temperature. The pile should feel hot. If it is air temperature then add more green waste to heat it up.</p>
      <p>After a few weeks of tending to your pile you’ll have a layer of good compost at the bottom of your bin. You can tell it’s ready if it’s dark and rich in color and you can’t differentiate any of the different materials in it. You can take this and begin adding it as a natural fertilizer to plants around your school.</p>

      <div class="action--nextstage callout">
